        summary: "Flashcard-style Q&A for transamination and deamination self-assessment.",
        contentMd: "# Active Recall\n\n**Q1:** What is the coenzyme required for transamination?\n> Pyridoxal phosphate (PLP), the active form of Vitamin B6\n\n**Q2:** Name the two clinically important transaminases.\n> ALT (SGPT) — liver-specific; AST (SGOT) — heart, liver, muscle\n\n**Q3:** What is the universal amino group acceptor in transamination?\n> Alpha-ketoglutarate (forms glutamate)\n\n**Q4:** Which enzyme performs oxidative deamination of glutamate?\n> Glutamate dehydrogenase (GDH) in mitochondria\n\n**Q5:** What activates and inhibits GDH?\n> Activated by ADP; Inhibited by GTP\n\n**Q6:** What is the De Ritis ratio? What values indicate alcoholic vs viral hepatitis?\n> AST/ALT ratio. >2 in alcoholic hepatitis; <1 in viral hepatitis\n\n**Q7:** Name the only two purely ketogenic amino acids.\n> Leucine and Lysine\n\n**Q8:** Why is pyridoxine given with isoniazid in TB treatment?\n> INH inactivates PLP (B6) by forming hydrazones; B6 deficiency causes neuropathy\n\n**Q9:** What is the glucose-alanine cycle?\n> Muscle transaminates amino acids to alanine, sends it to liver where alanine is converted back to pyruvate for gluconeogenesis, and NH2 enters urea cycle\n\n**Q10:** How does excess ammonia cause brain damage?\n> NH4+ drives glutamine synthesis in astrocytes, causing osmotic swelling and cerebral edema",
